# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode — Always

`tsconfig.json` has `"strict": true`. Never disable or cast away errors with `as any`.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
const data = response.data as any
const user = result as unknown as User

// ✅ GOOD — parse/validate with a type guard or zod
function isUser(val: unknown): val is User {
  return typeof val === 'object' && val !== null && 'id' in val && 'email' in val
}
```

## Shared Types

- Domain interfaces live in `lib/types/` and are imported everywhere — never define the same interface in multiple files.
- Use `interface` for object shapes; use `type` for unions, intersections, and mapped types.

```ts
// lib/types/user.ts
export interface User {
  id: string
  email: string
}

// lib/types/api.ts
export type ApiSuccess<T> = { data: T; error: null }
export type ApiError = { data: null; error: string }
export type ApiResult<T> = ApiSuccess<T> | ApiError
```

## Generic API Responses

Always use generics on axios calls so response shapes are typed end-to-end:

```ts
// ❌ BAD
const res = await apiClient.get('/api/auth/user')
const user = res.data.user // implicit any

// ✅ GOOD
const res = await apiClient.get<{ user: User }>('/api/auth/user')
const { user } = res.data
```

## No Implicit Returns / Undefined Paths

All functions that can return `undefined` must declare it in their return type. Use `satisfies` to verify object literals match a type without losing inference:

```ts
export const config = {
  supabaseUrl: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL!,
} satisfies Record<string, string>
```

## Enums → `as const` Objects

Avoid TypeScript `enum`. Use `as const` objects paired with a derived union type:

```ts
// ❌ BAD
enum Role { Admin = 'admin', Member = 'member' }

// ✅ GOOD
export const ROLE = { ADMIN: 'admin', MEMBER: 'member' } as const
export type Role = (typeof ROLE)[keyof typeof ROLE]
```
